```cpp
void DeviceStateMachine::RemoveStateChangeListener(int listener_id)
{
    std::lock_guard<std::mutex> lock(mutex_);
    listeners_.erase(
        std::remove_if(listeners_.begin(), listeners_.end(),
            [listener_id](const std::pair<int, StateCallback>& listener) {
                return listener.first == listener_id;
            }),
        listeners_.end());
}
```

This implementation:
- Locks the mutex to ensure thread safety.
- Uses `std::remove_if` to remove all elements matching the given `listener_id`.
- Erases the removed elements from the `listeners_` vector.

This pattern mirrors the use of `std::lock_guard` for protecting shared data and follows standard C++ idioms for removing elements from a container while iterating.

