```cpp
const char* WifiBoard::GetNetworkStateIcon() {
    auto& wifi = WifiManager::GetInstance();

    // If WiFi is not connected or in config mode, show offline icon
    if (wifi.IsConfigMode() || !wifi.IsConnected()) {
        return FONT_AWESOME_SIGNAL_OFF;
    }

    // Get RSSI value and map it to signal strength levels
    int rssi = wifi.GetRssi();

    // Typical RSSI to signal mapping:
    // -30 dBm to -60 dBm: Strong signal
    // -61 dBm to -70 dBm: Good signal
    // -71 dBm to -80 dBm: Fair signal
    // -81 dBm to -90 dBm: Weak signal
    // Below -90 dBm: Very poor signal

    if (rssi >= -60) {
        return FONT_AWESOME_SIGNAL_STRONG;
    } else if (rssi >= -70) {
        return FONT_AWESOME_SIGNAL_GOOD;
    } else if (rssi >= -80) {
        return FONT_AWESOME_SIGNAL_FAIR;
    } else if (rssi >= -90) {
        return FONT_AWESOME_SIGNAL_WEAK;
    } else {
        return FONT_AWESOME_SIGNAL_OFF; // Consider as no signal
    }
}
```

This approach reuses existing constants from `<font_awesome.h>` and follows the same logic used in other board implementations for representing network state visually. It leverages the already-available methods in `WifiManager` such as `IsConfigMode()`, `IsConnected()`, and `GetRssi()` to determine the appropriate icon.

