```cpp
std::string MqttProtocol::DecodeHexString(const std::string &hex_string)
{
    std::string result;
    result.reserve(hex_string.length() / 2);

    for (size_t i = 0; i < hex_string.length(); i += 2) {
        if (i + 1 < hex_string.length()) {
            uint8_t high = CharToHex(hex_string[i]);
            uint8_t low = CharToHex(hex_string[i + 1]);
            result.push_back((high << 4) | low);
        }
    }

    return result;
}
```

This implementation follows these patterns seen elsewhere in the codebase:
1. Uses the existing `CharToHex` helper function already defined in the file
2. Processes input in pairs of characters (since each byte is represented by two hex characters)
3. Performs bit shifting to combine high and low nibbles into bytes
4. Reserves memory upfront for efficiency
5. Handles edge cases like odd-length inputs gracefully

The function is used in the MQTT protocol initialization where it decodes AES encryption parameters received from the server:
